passages.text: We met with over 40 investors during marketig trip in Hong Kong over the past week. Overall, we continue to witness optimism among investors especially around AI sentiment, while interest level towards non- AI segments remain low. Key discussion with investors mainly focused on 1) TSMC's earnings growth outlook, capex trajectory towards 2027 and the implications to SPE, 2) debates on demand over ASICs vs AI GPU, 3) the dollar content growth outlook and the overview of competitive landscape shift within testing industry, and 4) advanced packaging demand trend, especially on CoWoS capacity outlook and the implications to CoWoS equipment vendors. Our key stock highlights including TSMC (Buy, on CL), MediaTek (Buy on CL), ASE (Buy), MPI (Buy), WinWay (Buy), GPTC (Buy), and All Ring (Buy). Below, we summarize the key takeaways from our meetings.
See also: Taiwan Technology: Growing chiplet adoption to unlock a new era of advanced packaging; Buy TSMC (on CL)/ASE/All Ring/GPTC (15 August 2025)

We reiterate our Buy rating on TSMC (on the Conviction List) and view it as one of the most underappreciated AI names with share price currently traded at only c.17x FY26 P/E. We also note that TSMC's share price (+12%) has largely unperformed other global key AI names YTD such as SK Hynix (+52%), Nvidia (+31%), Broadcom (+28%), AMD (+38%), etc. However, some pushback from investors was centered on a potential decelerating growth into 2026E. Nevertheless, we argue that we believe TSMC would continue to observe a re- rating with its ongoing strategy towards overseas capacity diversification. We feel that overall sentiment also further improved especially after the announcement of US semi tariff, from which TSMC is likely to be exempt (see also note). Furthermore, we continue to expect another strong growth year for TSMC into 2026E with revenue (in USD term) to grow by another 20% despite a robust 34% growth in 2025E, driven by the ramp up of 2nm/3nm nodes as well as the higher pricing for advanced nodes/packaging.

Capex trend as another key focus from investors given its implications to SPE names. TSMC's capex outlook is seen as moderate given capacity constraint with cleanroom availability to be the bottleneck in 2026, in our view. We are modeling capex of US \(40bn/US\) 42bn in 2025E/2026E. However, we are expecting a leap to US \(50bn in 2027E with positive implications towards WFE (wafer fab equipment)

Sentiment is relatively more divergent between long/short funds vs long- only funds. We feel that long- short funds were in generally holding a more negative view towards the name given the lack of near term catalysts, lukewarm smartphone market demand outlook and the continuous tape- out schedule delay of the TPU project. However, on the flip side, we sense that the AI ASIC TAM expansion theme remains compelling for long only investors, even as the first AI ASIC project tape- out timeline is now experiencing some setbacks. Nevertheless, the tape out timing of MediaTek's TPU project remains to be the key monitor point among most investors. Overall, we remain optimistic about MediaTek's ongoing TAM expansion into the US \(45bn ASIC market. As TPU becomes MediaTek's first stepping stone into this new TAM, we see a high likelihood of more CSP project wins going forward.

During our marketing trip, we consistently emphasized the increasing significance of the chiplet trend as the semiconductor industry transitions to more advanced process nodes. This evolution is a primary catalyst for the escalating demand for advanced packaging solutions. As detailed in our note: Taiwan Technology: Growing chiplet adoption to unlock a new era of advanced packaging; Buy TSMC (on CL)/ASE/All Ring/GPTC (15 August 2025), we underscored the substantial advantages of adopting chiplet designs. The inherent cost efficiencies and benefits of hybrid integration, facilitated by advanced packaging technologies such as CoWoS, are fostering wider adoption across diverse applications. This proliferation is notably expanding from AI into a broader spectrum of non- AI segments including server CPUs, networking chips, and other high- end consumer chips, etc. We believe this continuous penetration will drive a more sustained CoWoS/advanced packaging capacity expansion into 2027 and beyond. We are forecasting CoWoS shipment to reach 664k/1,080k/1,566k wafers and capacity of 675k/1,200k/1,740k wafers in 2025- 2027E.

Following the ongoing end application expansion for advanced packaging from AI to non- AI segments, we see OSAT (outsourced semiconductor assembly and test), i.e., ASE, are now ramping up its own advanced packaging capacity aggressively. We are modeling ASE/SPIL FOCoS- bridge and FOCoS- CL (corresponding to CoWoS- L and CoWoS- R) capacity to reach 5k/15k/30kwpm in 2025- 27E, representing 200%/100% YoY capacity increase in 2026/27E. We anticipate a US CPU provider to be primary adopter of its FOCoS- Bridge in 2026 for its upcoming new general server platform.

However, there was some pushback on the stock: 1) ASE's comparatively limited AI revenue contribution, estimated to be in the high- single- digits of its total revenue for 2025E, while its overall growth outlook still significantly influenced by the seasonality of mass- market consumer demand, and 2) a slower- than- anticipated recovery in GM. While the consensus among investors suggests ASE is currently perceived as an AI laggard

within the semiconductor industry, there is an observable willingness to revisit the name toward the end of the year early next year, as its AI- driven advanced packaging growth accelerates into 2026.

We see rising interest from investors especially over the past several weeks post share price corrections for CoWoS equipment names, especially for GPTC (Buy) and All Ring (Buy), of which share prices were down \(9 - 13\%\) since the recent peak in June (vs Taiex up \(9\%\) ) given investors concern regarding 2026 growth prospects, driven by differing views on next year's CoWoS capacity expansion. However, we contend that investors may have underestimated the capacity contributions from OSAT sides. Combining our estimates for TSMC and ASE/SPIL, we forecast total CoWoS capacity to reach approximately a total of \(80k / 135k / 200k\) of CoWoS capacity at end 2025- 2027E, implying net addition of \(55k / 65k\) in 2026/2027E, higher vs the \(44k\) new addition in 2025E.

We are seeing rising investor interests towards the testing names such as MPI (Buy), WinWay (Buy), and Hon Precision (7769. TVO, not covered), as these names were brought up by investors constantly during our meetings. We continue to push for the increasing dollar content theme for advanced testing industry, as we highlighted in our initiation report: Unlocking the golden era of advanced chip testing: initiate MPI/WinWay at Buy; TP NT \(1,000 / NT\) 1,500 (25 May 2025), that we are seeing an unstoppable structural trend of more complex chip designs as migrating into more advanced nodes with higher standards of testing requirements.

In terms of growth outlook, we have emphasized that both MPI/WinWay will be benefiting from the growing ASP trend following the ongoing technology migration with higher pin count trend. While MPI/WinWay currently hold only a \(7\% /8\%\) of global market share within probe card/socket market, respectively, we expect this will gradually grow to \(11\% /14\%\) by 2027E. We also see potential new opportunity for the two names to penetrate into new AI GPU supply chain. Overall, we are modeling an earnings CAGR of \(37\% /34\%\) for MPI/WinWay from 2024- 2027E, driven by both organic industry growth and share gains.
Key risks to our views: 1) softer AI/HPC demand, 2) slower penetration into new TAM, and 3) intensifying competition.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
